<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>
<subsection xml:id="lec-redondearYRedondearOtraVez" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">

<shorttitle>Lección 16 </shorttitle>
<title>Lección 16 -<nbsp/></title>
<title>Redondeemos y redondeemos otra vez</title>


<!-- ============================================ 
  Objetivos de aprendizaje                        
=================================================  -->

<!-- Frase resumen para estudiante. Originalmente [Student Facing Goals] -->
<introduction component="est-goal"> 
  <p>Busquemos patrones al redondear.</p>
</introduction>

<!-- Objetivos para el estudiante. Originalmente [Student-Facing Targets] -->
<!-- <objectives component="estudiante">
  <ul>
    <li>[@@@@@@@@@@@@@@]</li>
  </ul>
</objectives> -->

<!-- Objetivos que solo ve el profesor. Originalmente [Teacher Facing Goals] -->
<objectives component="profesor">
  <ul>
    <li><p>[++++++++++++++++]</p></li>
    <li><p>Recognize and generalize patterns in the rounding of whole numbers within 1,000.</p></li>
  </ul>
</objectives>


<!-- ============================================ 
  Introducción para el profesor                        
=================================================  -->
<introduction component="profesor">

  <!-- Estándares CCSS asociados -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="ccss-leccion-titulo"/></title> 
    <ul>
      <li> 
        <custom ref="ccss-addressing"/>
        <xref ref="ccss-3-NBT-A-1" text="custom">3.NBT.A.1</xref>,
        <xref ref="ccss-3-OA-C-7" text="custom">3.OA.C.7</xref>
      </li>
    </ul>
    </paragraphs>

  <!-- índice de la lección (automático) -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="timeline-leccion-titulo"/></title>
    <list-of elements="subsubsection reading-questions" scope="subsection"/>
  </paragraphs>

  <!-- Propósito de la lección -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="purpose-leccion-titulo"/></title>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <p>The purpose of this lesson is for students to use their understanding of rounding to consider all the numbers that round to a given number.</p>
  </paragraphs>

  <!-- Materiales requeridos -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="materials-leccion-titulo"/></title>
    <!-- <ul>
      <li>
        <p>Actividad 1</p>
        <xi:include href="./act-todosLosNum-mat.ptx"/>
        <xi:include href="./act-todosLosNum-matCentros.ptx"/>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Actividad 2</p>
        <xi:include href="./act-cualEsMiNumSecreto-mat.ptx"/>
        <xi:include href="./act-cualEsMiNumSecreto-matCentros.ptx"/>
      </li>
    </ul>  -->
  </paragraphs>
  
  <!-- Introducción de la lección (narrative) -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="narrative-leccion-titulo"/></title>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <p>Students deepen their understanding of rounding to go beyond accurately rounding individual numbers as they think about what numbers round to a given number. Working backward from a multiple of 10 or 100 allows students to think about the relative distance of numbers and the range of numbers that round to the given multiple of 10 or 100. Students then use this understanding to write clues to help their classmates guess a mystery number. What a number rounds to becomes a useful way to describe a number in this game.</p>
  </paragraphs>
  
  <!-- Preguntas de reflexión profesor -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="reflection-quest-titulo"/></title>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <p>What was the best question you asked students today? Why would you consider it the best one based on what students said or did?</p>
  </paragraphs>
</introduction>


